[[File:FindMe.jpg|right|thumb|Cover of the book ''Find Me'']]

'''''Find Me''''' is a memoir written by comedian, actress, and [[talk show]] host [[Rosie O'Donnell]]. It was published in 2002.

The book, which reached number two on the ''[[New York Times]]'' bestseller list,<ref>{{en icon}} [https://www.nytimes.com/2002/06/02/books/best-sellers-june-2-2002.html?pagewanted=all&src=pm BEST SELLERS: June 2, 2002] - ''New York Times''</ref> is, at heart, a remembrance of O'Donnell's troubled childhood. It also tells the story of O'Donnell's involvement with a woman who has [[multiple personality disorder]] who initially claims to be the mother of a [[pregnant]] 14-year-old girl and later that very girl and, even later on, the girl's father.

O'Donnell professes her own compulsion to try to rescue others from their negative situations and details her inability to listen to the reason of those around her who urge her not to pursue the situation.

It precedes O'Donnell's latest memoir, ''[[Celebrity Detox|Celebrity Detox:The Fame Game]]'', which was published October 9, 2007.

