The '''gown-and-glove striptease''' is considered a very traditional form of the [[striptease]].<ref name="la times">{{cite web |last1=Chun |first1=Alex |title=Clean, wholesome, old-fashioned burlesque |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2008/feb/14/entertainment/gd-movies14 |website=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=24 November 2018 |date=14 February 2008}}</ref><ref name="10 Steps">{{cite web |title=10 Steps to Classic Burlesque Superstardom - The Ultimate Masterclass |url=http://21stcenturyburlesque.com/10-steps-classic-burlesque-striptease-masterclass/ |website=21st Century Burlesque Magazine |accessdate=24 November 2018 |date=29 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Southern Fried Burlesque Festival has curve appeal |url=https://creativeloafing.com/content-168705-Southern-Fried-Burlesque-Festival-has-curve-appeal |website=Atlanta Creative Loafing |accessdate=24 November 2018 |language=en |date=9 March 2011}}</ref> This routine developed in American and spread to Europe.<ref name="10 Steps" /> The performer, usually female, is dressed elegantly in an [[evening gown]] with a [[back zipper]] and elbow length [[Evening gloves|opera gloves]]. She then removes the gloves one at a time, in a slow teasing manner, before similarly removing the gown. This type of dance is exemplified by actresses like [[Rita Hayworth]] in ''[[Gilda]]'' (1946)<ref>{{cite web |title=Gilda: Rita Hayworth as Gilda Farrell |url=https://girlsdofilm.wordpress.com/2013/07/15/gilda-rita-hayworth-as-gilda-farrell/ |website=Girls Do Film |accessdate=24 November 2018 |date=15 July 2013}}</ref> and [[Natalie Wood]] in ''[[Gypsy (1962 film)|Gypsy]]'' (1962)<ref>{{cite book |last1=Whitesell |first1=Lloyd |title=Wonderful Design: Glamour in the Hollywood Musical |date=2018 |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |isbn=9780190843847 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=lCRjDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT33&lpg=PT33&dq=Natalie+Wood+gown+and+glove+striptease&source=bl&ots=ejr97288Mu&sig=vsphHANk4FQsPvYwLCAiKwMKQFQ&hl=en&sa