{{Infobox award | name = Queen Elizabeth II Coronation Award | image = | imagesize = | caption = | description = Contributions to ballet and dance | presenter = [[Royal Academy of Dance]] | country = {{UK}} | year = 1953 | website = http://www.rad.org.uk }}
The '''Queen Elizabeth II Coronation Award''' is an honour presented annually by the [[Royal Academy of Dance]], to people who have made a significant contribution to the ballet and dance industry. The award was instituted by [[Dame Adeline Genee]] in 1953, to mark the coronation of [[Elizabeth II of the United Kingdom|Queen Elizabeth II]] and her appointment as Royal Patron of the Academy. The first winner of the award was [[Ninette de Valois|Dame Ninette de Valois]], founder of the [[Royal Ballet]], [[Birmingham Royal Ballet]] and [[Royal Ballet School]]. The award has since been presented to a number of notable people, and is recognised as the highest honour awarded by the Academy.
